@startuml C4_Code_DeviceRepository
' Level 4 — Code
' Zoom into the Device Repository component.
' Show the key architectural abstraction: interface + two implementations.
' This pattern (Repository Interface) solves the monolith problem
' where SQL was scattered across all code and replacing the DB was impossible.

title Class Diagram — Device Repository (Device Management Service)

' ─── Repository Interface ───
' Business logic (services) depends only on the interface, not the concrete implementation.
' Allows changing the DB without modifying logic and writing unit tests with mock implementations.
interface DeviceRepository {
    + FindByID(ctx Context, id DeviceID) : Device, error
    + FindByHomeID(ctx Context, homeID HomeID) : []Device, error
    + Save(ctx Context, device Device) : Device, error
    + Update(ctx Context, device Device) : Device, error
    + Delete(ctx Context, id DeviceID) : error
    + UpdateState(ctx Context, id DeviceID, state DeviceState) : error
}

' ─── PostgreSQL Implementation ───
class PostgresDeviceRepository {
    - pool : *pgxpool.Pool
    + FindByID(ctx Context, id DeviceID) : Device, error
    + FindByHomeID(ctx Context, homeID HomeID) : []Device, error
    + Save(ctx Context, device Device) : Device, error
    + Update(ctx Context, device Device) : Device, error
    + Delete(ctx Context, id DeviceID) : error
    + UpdateState(ctx Context, id DeviceID, state DeviceState) : error
}

' ─── Mock Implementation for Tests ───
' Does not access the real DB — allows testing services in isolation.
class InMemoryDeviceRepository {
    - storage : map[DeviceID]Device
    + FindByID(ctx Context, id DeviceID) : Device, error
    + FindByHomeID(ctx Context, homeID HomeID) : []Device, error
    + Save(ctx Context, device Device) : Device, error
    + Update(ctx Context, device Device) : Device, error
    + Delete(ctx Context, id DeviceID) : error
    + UpdateState(ctx Context, id DeviceID, state DeviceState) : error
}

' ─── Services depend on the interface, not the implementation ───
class DeviceRegistrationService {
    - repo : DeviceRepository
    - protocolAdapter : ProtocolAdapter
    + Execute(ctx Context, cmd RegisterDeviceCommand) : Device, error
}

class DeviceStateService {
    - repo : DeviceRepository
    - protocolAdapter : ProtocolAdapter
    - eventPublisher : EventPublisher
    + Execute(ctx Context, cmd SendCommandRequest) : error
}

' ─── Domain Model ───
class Device {
    + ID : DeviceID
    + HomeID : HomeID
    + RoomID : RoomID
    + Type : DeviceType
    + Protocol : Protocol
    + State : DeviceState
    + LastSeen : time.Time
    + CreatedAt : time.Time
}

enum DeviceType {
    TEMPERATURE_SENSOR
    LIGHT_SWITCH
    SMART_LOCK
    CAMERA
    THERMOSTAT
    RELAY
}

enum Protocol {
    MQTT
    MATTER
    ZIGBEE
    HTTP
}

' ─── Relations ───
DeviceRepository <|.. PostgresDeviceRepository : implements
DeviceRepository <|.. InMemoryDeviceRepository : implements

DeviceRegistrationService --> DeviceRepository : uses
DeviceStateService --> DeviceRepository : uses

DeviceRegistrationService ..> Device : creates
DeviceStateService ..> Device : updates

Device --> DeviceType
Device --> Protocol

note right of Device
  All IDs (DeviceID, HomeID, RoomID) are distinct types,
  not plain strings or integers.
  This prevents passing a HomeID where a DeviceID
  is expected — caught at compile time, not at runtime.
end note

note right of DeviceRepository
  Interface — the key abstraction.
  Services depend only on it.
  The concrete implementation (Postgres, Mock)
  is injected via a DI container.
  This eliminates the main monolith problem:
  SQL was everywhere; replacing the DB = refactoring everything.
end note

note bottom of InMemoryDeviceRepository
  Used in unit tests.
  Allows testing business logic
  without running PostgreSQL.
end note

@enduml
